        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(center)">I</p>
            <p rend="align(right)">1</p>
            <p>Rev. Sir!</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I was much gratified in reading the <date>Oct.</date> of<lb/> last
                month, to see your able remarks, in <sic>refference</sic> to<lb/> the late trial of
                the <persName>Rev. Rosenfeld</persName> this is as it should<lb/> be, I mean, that
                the accusers have had an equal share<lb/> of justice done them at your hands;
                several learned<lb/> persons were invited as visitors to attend the
                investi,<lb/>gation of that case. None went, because they knew, that<lb/> such
                question can only be examined by a qualified<lb/> and legal tribunal.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">This affair induces me to crave your able assistance<lb/> in a
                    <sic>Rabinical</sic>—and a Religious—Question, which<lb/> has been
                    <sic>referd</sic> to me for a decision;<lb/> There was a grand Procession here
                in <placeName>Cincinnati</placeName><lb/> among the fraternity of the Free Masons in
                honor<lb/> to —”—. several <add>Hebrew</add> in this procession which took<lb/> an
                active part. Among this Number, was the <persName>Rev<lb/> Mr R.</persName> &amp;
                    <persName>Mr I.</persName> a <add>Hebrew</add> the head of this Procession<lb/>
                the Order of Knight Templar Jerusalem marched with<lb/> their crosses emblematic of
                their order, when near<lb/> the church, the Order of the Templars were
                station,<lb/>ed in a manner, so that the entire body of the<lb/> masons, marched
                slowly &amp; solemnly &amp; passed before<lb/> them <hi rend="underline"
                        ><sic>reverentialy</sic></hi> bowing, with their <sic>hads</sic>
                <sic>uncoverd</sic>,<lb/> the two gentlemen named as above did the same,<lb/> the
                    <add>Hebrew</add> who were present and witnessed these procee,<lb/>,dings
                declare that it <sic>appeard</sic> to them as wicked<lb/>
                <sic>Idolitary</sic>, it is also <sic>alledged</sic> that they went<lb/> through the
                same ceremony in the church, and attended<lb/> the Banquet in the Evening.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I must confess my entire ignorance in the<lb/> Mysteries of Masonry,
                but I may be allowed to know<lb/> something of the History and Origin of the K.
                Templ.<lb/> There is a considerable <sic>dificulties</sic>, from various causes<lb/>
                to find persons willingly to take cognizance in this matter</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p rend="align(center)">II</p>
            <p rend="align(right)">2</p>
            <p>whence the question is pressed on me for a <sic>definate</sic><lb/> answer, but for
                the want of assistance it is not<lb/> proper for me to give a peremptory
                decision.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">All that I am enabled to do, in the present instance<lb/> is to
                point out the Law as laid down by <add>Hebrew</add> in the<lb/> different places and
                as under are the passages I have selected.</p>
            <p>
                <add>Hebrew</add>
            </p>
            <p>These Regulations &amp; Rules of the Talmud and the most important<lb/> Dasuites and
                even as proofed of the holy <add>Hebrew</add>, by the <sic>comentators</sic><lb/>
                are received by us Jews as standard Law, and as such it is<lb/> my opinion they
                should be respected!</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Which reflecting on these proceeding I am led to<lb/> place these
                construction, namely, for a <sic>jew</sic> to pay a<lb/> reverential
                    <sic>diferrence</sic> to the K. Templar is unnatural,<lb/> because they are in
                the <del>wildes</del> mildest of terms—<lb/>the <sic>enimy</sic> of our holy Faith.
                To pay homage to<lb/> a cross. Figure or Picture (empleme or not) which
                represents<lb/> one thing to the Eye and another to the understanding is
                Idolatry!</p>
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p rend="align(center)">III</p>
            <p rend="align(right)">3</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">To pay respect to the crucifix is an evidence in<lb/> favour
                Christianity, but as we Jews do not <del>regog</del> recognize<lb/> a Trinity and
                being strictly <sic>forbiden</sic> against <del>my king</del><lb/> making my
                likeness what ever, neither to bow nor to worship or to show<lb/> any adoration or
                veneration.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Our belief is in an undivided and in an omnipotent God<lb/> and to
                Him alone it is our duty to pay Adoration and<lb/> Humiliation—<add>Hebrew</add>!
                either in thought, word or deed!<lb/> This is the construction to which I have on
                reflection arrived.<lb/> Now, my dear Sir! if you feel any desire, or consider
                it<lb/> proper to take any notice of this subject, it is my<lb/> humble opinion that
                you will greatly sever the public<lb/> by answering this or call upon of this
                through your<lb/> useful &amp; valuable Journal for to do so</p>
            <p rend="indent(10)">
                <persName role="author">Dr. I Mayer</persName>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">
                <placeName>Cincinnati</placeName>
                <date>Novemb: 24. 5613</date>
            </p>
